Purpose

Focusing only on DNase vs untreated samples? - Are there taxa only present in non-dnase samples? - Are there certain taxa that are only extracellular?

As expected, the dnase samples are less complex and seem to be dominated by one or two taxa, whereas the non-dnase samples are more complex.

summary_genus <- ps_melt %>%
        group_by(Genus, dnase, fraction) %>%

summary_genus$dnase_p <- summary_genus$dnase
summary_genus$dnase_p[summary_genus$dnase == "yes"] <- "sample+DNase"
summary_genus$dnase_p[summary_genus$dnase == "no"] <- "sample"

plot <- summary_genus %>%
  filter(Genus == "Clostridium sensu stricto 18") %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(x = dnase_p, y = Abundance)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("") + 
  theme(legend.position = "none") + ylab("Relative Abundance (%)") + 
  ggtitle("Clostridium")
  

clos_summary <- summary_genus %>% 
  filter(Genus == "Clostridium sensu stricto 18")
  
stat.test <- compare_means(Abundance ~ dnase_p, data = clos_summary, method = "wilcox.test", p.adjust.method = "fdr")
## Adding missing grouping variables: `Genus`, `dnase`, `fraction`
FigS4a <- plot + stat_pvalue_manual(stat.test, label = "p.adj", y.position = 110) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.05, 0.15)))

Alpha diversity

meta_ps <- meta_ps %>% 
  mutate(estimate_richness(ps, measures = c("Observed", "Shannon", "InvSimpson"))) %>% 
  mutate(microbiome::evenness(ps, "pielou"))

sample_data(ps) <- meta_ps


meta_dnase <- meta_ps %>% 
  filter(fraction != "mock_community" & dnase != "neg")
# kruskal test
kruskal.test(meta_dnase$Observed ~ meta_dnase$dnase)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  meta_dnase$Observed by meta_dnase$dnase
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 11.158, df = 1, p-value = 0.0008368
kruskal.test(meta_dnase$Shannon ~ meta_dnase$dnase)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  meta_dnase$Shannon by meta_dnase$dnase
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 7.4636, df = 1, p-value = 0.006296
kruskal.test(meta_dnase$InvSimpson ~ meta_dnase$dnase)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  meta_dnase$InvSimpson by meta_dnase$dnase
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 6.9644, df = 1, p-value = 0.008315
meta_ps_long <- melt(meta_dnase) %>% filter(variable %in% c("Shannon", "Observed", "pielou", "InvSimpson"))
## Using patient_ID, fraction, dnase, is.neg, extraction, sam_names, disease as id variables
meta_ps_long$dnase_p <- meta_ps_long$dnase
meta_ps_long$dnase_p[meta_ps_long$dnase == "yes"] <- "sample+\nDNase"
meta_ps_long$dnase_p[meta_ps_long$dnase == "no"] <- "sample"


my_comparisons <- list(c("sample+\nDNase", "sample"))


adiv_dnase <- meta_ps_long %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(x = dnase_p, y = value)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_bw() +
  #guides(fill=guide_legend(title="")) +
  #theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()) +
  facet_wrap(~variable, scales = "free", nrow = 1) + 
  xlab("") + ylab("")


stat.test <- compare_means(value ~ dnase_p, data = meta_ps_long,  group.by = "variable", method = "wilcox.test", p.adjust.method = "fdr")

Fig4c <- adiv_dnase + stat_pvalue_manual(stat.test, label = "p.adj", y.position = c(20, 3, 13, 1.05)) + scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.05, 0.15)))
